### Scoring Rationale
The paper's central RL findings — the +2.3 hybrid improvement, training collapse, reward hacking dynamics — all rest on single-run experiments with no seed variance reported. This is a critical failure by ICLR empirical standards. The confounded prompting design (untrained verifiers get simplified prompts, trained verifiers get full question context) means the "accuracy-RL mismatch" could stem from prompt differences rather than fine-tuning. The adversarial probing is limited to surface-level syntactic patterns, and no baseline RL mitigations (KL regularization, DAPO) are tested.

The paper is stronger than DeepCritic (4.7) in its cleaner motivation and actionable discriminative-vs-generative finding. But it's substantially weaker than the contamination paper (6.7) due to the single-run issue and confounded experimental design. The contamination paper had proper multi-seed controls, formal theorem support, and clear ablations. This paper lacks that rigor while making similarly central RL claims.

The paper sits at approximately 4.6 — above DeepCritic's range given cleaner problem setup and more actionable insights, but below the reject/accept boundary due to the critical single-run and confounding weaknesses.

